[Comment "queens-indian-defense-tournament-edition/course/2358, variation/78953"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6 5. b3 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Be7 7. Bg2 c6 8. O-O d5 
9. Qc2 {White develops his queen to c2.} O-O 10. Rd1 Nbd7 11. Bf4 Rc8 {Black 
prepares the usual c7-c5 pawn advance.} 12. Nc3 Nh5 {A nice move that threatens 
to trade off White's bishop on f4.} 13. Bc1 {White wants to keep the bishop 
pair.} f5 {An aggressive move that shows that Black is playing for a win. Black 
can also retreat the knight to f6, which often leads to a move repetition after 
the bishop returns to f4.} *

