[SourceTitle "02 Petrosian Variation"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "queens-indian-defense-tournament-edition/course/2358, variation/78934"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 {This move signifies the Petrosian 
Variation.} Bb7 5. Nc3 d5 {It is very logical to challenge White's center.} 6. 
Bg5 Be7 7. e3 {Now that the bishop is outside of the pawn chain, White can play 
e3.} O-O 8. Rc1 Nbd7 {Black is developing his knight and preparing a c7-c5 
advance} 9. cxd5 exd5 {This is the best way of recapturing the pawn because 
Black maintains a grip on the e4 square, which prevents White from pushing 
forward in the center with e3-e4.} 10. Bd3 c5 {With the knight on d7, Black is 
prepared to make this advance.} 11. O-O Ne4 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. dxc5 bxc5 {Black's 
position is quite good: he has pawns in the center and his pieces are 
developed.} *

[Event "Queen's Indian Defense- Tournament Edition"]
