[SourceTitle "02 Petrosian Variation"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "queens-indian-defense-tournament-edition/course/2358, variation/78935"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 d5 6. Bg5 Be7 7. Bxf6 {This is one 
of White's options.} Bxf6 8. cxd5 exd5 {It is incredibly important to maintain 
control of the e4-square as long as White still has his e-pawn because it 
prevents any e2-e4 pawn advance ideas that White might have.} 9. g3 O-O 10. Bg2 
c5 {Black has the bishop pair, so he wants to open up the position as much as 
possible.} 11. O-O Na6 {Black supports the c-pawn and prepares interesting 
maneuvering ideas such as Na6-c7-e6.} *

