[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "queens-indian-defense-tournament-edition/course/2358, variation/78936"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 d5 6. Bg5 Be7 7. Qa4+ {Yet another 
option White has in this line.} Bc6 {Although this is not the most frequently 
played move, databases seem to show that it is the latest trend. It also scores 
much higher than the most played move c7-c6.} 8. Qb3 {If White plays Qc2 
instead, Black should still take on c4.} dxc4 9. Qxc4 O-O 10. Bxf6 {Black's 
knight on f6 was an important piece because it added support to the e4-square. 
By trading it off, White prepares the pawn advance e2-e4.} Bxf6 11. e4 Bb7 
{White has a bigger center, but Black has the bishop pair and can get good play 
with an eventual pawn break such as c7-c5.} *

